      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "To the best of our knowledge, only TICO-19, a health domain translation benchmark, has the potential to be used for document-level MT, while it is restricted to topics related to COVID-19."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q15",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Document-level NMT aims to overcome the limitations of sentence-level systems by translating an entire document as a whole."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q16",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Both document-level and context-aware MT allow for the possibility of improving translation quality for context-dependent phenomena such as coreference resolution (Müller et al., 2018; Bawden et al., 2018; Voita et al., 2018; Herold and Ney, 2023), lexical disambiguation (Rios Gonzales et al., 2017; Martínez Garcia et al., 2019), and lexical cohesion (Wong and Kit, 2012; Garcia et al., 2014, 2017; Bawden et al., 2018; Voita et al., 2019)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q17",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Various methods have been proposed to extend sentence-level models to capture document-level context (Tiedemann and Scherrer, 2017; Libovický and Helcl, 2017; Bawden et al., 2018; Miculicich et al., 2018; Sun et al., 2022)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q18",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We scraped English articles from the websites of Techpoint Africa and the World Health Organization (WHO). The articles cover different topics of different lengths with an average length of 30 and 37 sentences for health and tech respectively."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q19",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "While our corpus is initially structured at the article level, we aim to make it suitable for sentence-level translation tasks as well."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q20",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To achieve this, we segmented the raw articles into sentences using NLTK (Bird et al., 2009)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q21",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To ensure high segmentation quality, we recruited a linguist and a professional translator to verify the correctness of the segmentation and make corrections as needed."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q22",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Finally, we selected 334 and 271 English articles/documents from the health and tech domains respectively, which represents 10k sentences each per domain."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q23",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We translated the extracted 10k English sentences to the 5 African languages through 4 expert translators per language."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q24",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The translators were recruited through a language coordinator who is also a native speaker of the language."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q25",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The 10k sentences were distributed equally among the translators and the translations were done in-context (i.e. the translators translated on the sentence level but had access to the whole document)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q26",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Due to the domain-specific nature of the task, before starting the translation process, we conducted a translation workshop, during which three translation experts shared their experiences in creating terminologies and they also shared existing resources with the translators including short translation guidelines (Appendix A.1)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q27",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Quality control was conducted using automated quality estimation, followed by manual inspections by our language coordinators."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q28",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We also used Quality Estimation (QE), specifically AfriCOMET (Wang et al., 2024a), Given a translated sentence in any African language and its corresponding source English sentence, AfriCOMET generates a score between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates poor quality and higher values signify better quality."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q29",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The translators, in collaboration with the language coordinators, were tasked with reviewing instances that had quality estimation scores below 0.65."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q30",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Manual inspection indicates that QE scores below 0.65 do not necessarily reflect poor translations, consistent with Adelani et al. (2024b), likely due to"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q31",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Each translator was paid $1, 250 for 2, 500 sentences."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q32",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We created train, development (dev), and test splits for each domain. To prevent data leakage, documents sharing sentences with the same English translation were assigned to the training set. The dev set contains 25–33 documents, and the test set 59–61 documents, drawn from the remaining data."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q33",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Table 4 shows the average number of whitespace-separated tokens per sentence across domains and languages, including English. The health domain has more tokens than tech. Hausa and Yorùbá are longer than English, likely due to their descriptive nature, while Swahili is similar in length. Amharic and Zulu are relatively shorter, reflecting interesting linguistic properties."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q34",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The health data is licensed under CC BY-NCSA 3.0, while the tech data is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q35",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Given the AFRIDOC-MT data, we conducted both sentence- and document-level translation, evaluating two types of models: encoder-decoder and decoder-only models. While the majority of these models are open-source, we also evaluated two proprietary models of the same type."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q36",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Our evaluation primarily focuses on document-level translation, reflecting the availability of our document-level translation corpus. For completeness, we also conduct a series of sentence-level experiments, with the results presented in Appendix C."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q37",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We evaluate five kinds of open encoder-decoder model including Toucan (Elmadany et al., 2024; Adebara et al., 2024), M2M-100 (Fan et al., 2020), NLLB200 (NLLB Team et al., 2024), MADLAD400 (Kudugunta et al., 2023), and Aya-101 (Üstün et al., 2024)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q38",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Toucan is an Afro-centric multilingual MT model supporting 150 African language pairs. In comparison, M2M-100, NLLB-200, and MADLAD-400 cover between 100 and 450 language pairs. Aya-101, an instruction-tuned mT5 model (Xue et al., 2021), supports 100 languages and can translate between various languages, including those considered in AFRIDOC-MT."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q39",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We also evaluate open and closed decoder-only models. Open models include LLama3.1 (Dubey et al., 2024), Gemma2 (Gemma Team et al., 2024), their instruction-tuned variants, and LLaMAX3 (Lu et al., 2024)—a LLama3-based model further pre-trained on 100+ languages, including several African ones. The closed models include OpenAI GPT models (GPT-3.5 Turbo and GPT-4o) (OpenAI, 2024), which have been shown to have document-level translation ability (Wang et al., 2023)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q40",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "While their language coverage is not well documented, they show some ability to handle African languages (Adelani et al., 2024b; Bayes et al., 2024), though far below their performance in English, their primary training language."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q41",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We present the result of 12 models in total, including the 1.2B version of Toucan, 1.3B and 3.3B versions of NLLB-200, 3B and 13B versions of MADLAD-400 and Aya-101 respectively. We also have the 8B instruction tuned version of LLama3.1 (LLama3.1-IT), 9B version of Gemma-2 (Gemma2-IT), and LLaMAX3-Alpaca."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q42",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For sentence-level evaluation, we jointly fine-tune NLLB-200 with 1.3B parameters on the 30 language directions and on the two domains to make the models more specialized. Similarly, we did supervised fine-tuning (SFT) on LLaMAX3"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q43",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We perform SFT on LLaMAX3 and LLama3.1 for document-level translation, using pseudo-documents with k=10."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q44",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Given that our created dataset can be used for sentence-level translation and as a baseline for document-level translation, we evaluate all models on the test splits for each domain."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q45",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We evaluate the translation models (M2M-100, NLLB-200, and MADLAD-400) using the Fairseq (Ott et al., 2019) codebase for (M2M-100 and NLLB-200), and the Transformers (Wolf et al., 2020) codebase for MADLAD-400."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q46",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, for other models including Aya-101, we use the EleutherAI LM Evaluation Harness (lm-eval) tool (Biderman et al., 2024) using the three templates listed in Table 23 of Appendix B.4."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q47",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "An initial analysis showed that some models were unable to process entire documents due to input length limits, which were exceeded by token counts in some languages (Amharic and Yorùbá)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q48",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To address this, we adopted a similar approach to Lee et al. (2022), splitting documents into fixed-size chunks of k sentences to fit within token limits; the final chunk may contain fewer than k sentences."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q49",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To select an appropriate chunk size, we conducted initial tests with k = 1 (sentence-level), 5, 10, and 25, choosing k = 10 for our experiments."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q50",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Evaluating document-level translation remains challenging, as existing automatic metrics struggle to capture improvements and account for discourse phenomena (Jiang et al., 2022; Dahan et al., 2024), and embedding-based metrics have not been explored in this context for African languages due to the lack of data."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q51",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Hence, we realigned sentence-level or pseudo-translation outputs into full documents, then computed BLEU (Papineni et al., 2002) and chrF (Popović, 2015) to create document BLEU (d-BLEU) and document chrF (d-chrF)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q52",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Metrics were computed using SacreBLEU (Post, 2018) with bootstrap resampling (n = 1000) to report 95% confidence intervals."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q53",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We report d-chrF scores for the best prompt per model and language direction in the main text, as chrF better captures the morphological richness of African languages (Adelani et al., 2022), with full results provided in Appendix C."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q54",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We use GPT-4o as a judge to evaluate translation outputs, following recent work showing LLMs' effectiveness in assessing translation quality and analyzing errors (Wu et al., 2024; Sun et al., 2025)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q55",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Following Sun et al. (2025), we assess each translated document's fluency, content errors (CE), and cohesion errors—specifically lexical (LE) and grammatical (GE) errors—using GPT-4o, with evaluation limited to a few model outputs due to cost constraints (Appendix B.6)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q56",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We also complement this with human evaluation for direct assessment scores (Appendix B.7) and qualitative analysis through manual inspection (Appendix B.8)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q57",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In Tables 5 and 6 we present d-chrF scores based on the realigned documents, created by merging the translated sentences into their corresponding documents."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q58",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "On average the NLLB models obtain scores of 65.4/66.6 and 64.3/65.0 on health and tech domains respectively, with 3.3B outperforming 1.3B except when translating into Yorùbá."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q59",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Furthermore, translating to African languages is significantly worse compared to translating to English for all the models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q60",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In Tables 7 and 8 we present d-chrF scores based on the best prompt per language for the translation output of the models when evaluated on the realigned documents from pseudo-documents with k =10 sentences per pseudo-document."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q61",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Pseudo-document translation is worse than sentence-level translation when translating into African languages Our results from pseudo-document translation show a performance drop across different models compared to sentence-level translation, especially when translating into African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q62",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, GPT-4o demonstrates similar and consistent performance in both setups and domains."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q63",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Additionally, we observe that GPT-3.5 is the next best performing decoder-only LLM, which contrasts with its performance in sentence-level translation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q64",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Table 9 presents average GPT-4o evaluations for fluency and content errors (CE) of realigned outputs from sentence-level and pseudo-document-level tasks (k=10) across four models in the health domain."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q65",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "When translating into English, pseudo-document outputs are generally rated as more fluent and show fewer content errors, except for LLaMAX3-SFT1, which, when evaluated on pseudo-documents, shows lower fluency but still fewer content errors—an outcome that is counterintuitive."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q66",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "However, when translating into African languages, the results are less consistent."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q67",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "These inconsistencies raise concerns about GPT-4o's reliability."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q68",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Consequently, we focus on human evaluation going forward."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q69",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In Table 10 we report average direct assessment (DA) scores (on a scale from 0 to 100) from three annotators per language for the health domain, when translating into four African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q70",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "For each language, we used 30 documents across models and both domains to compute inter-annotator"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q71",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We obtained Krippendorff's alpha values of ≥ 0.40, which are relatively low due to the fine granularity of the evaluation scale."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q72",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Human evaluation results align closely with d-chrF, which favors sentence-level translations over pseudo-document translations when translating into African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q73",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Among the models, LLaMAX3-SFT1 receives higher ratings at the sentence-level but is rated lower when translating pseudo-documents."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q74",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In contrast, LLaMAX3-SFT10 receives slightly lower ratings than LLaMAX3-SFT1 at the sentence-level but is rated higher in the pseudo-document setting."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q75",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "GPT-3.5 is generally rated as the weakest model across languages, except for Swahili, where its performance is comparatively better."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q76",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Our qualitative analysis, based on feedback from native speakers who are also authors, indicates that GPT-3.5 frequently over-generates in the pseudo-document setup by repeating words and phrases—except in Swahili, where it performs best."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q77",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "However, for Yorùbá, it often uses inconsistent or partial diacritics, resulting in inaccuracies."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q78",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "LLaMAX3-SFT1 also exhibits repetition in pseudo-document translations, likely due to a length generalization problem (Anil et al., 2022), and does so more than LLaMAX3-SFT10."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q79",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For the other four languages, LLaMAX3-SFT1 with the sentence-level setup was rated higher than other models and configurations, owing to better context preservation and fewer repetitions."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q80",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We introduce AFRIDOC-MT, a document-level translation dataset in the health and tech domains for five African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q81",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We benchmarked various models, fine-tuning selected ones."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q82",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Due to context length limits, documents were translated either sentence by sentence or as pseudo-documents."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q83",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Outputs were evaluated using standard MT metrics, GPT-4o as a judge, and human direct assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q84",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "NLLB-200 was the strongest built-in MT model, while GPT-4o outperformed general-purpose LLMs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q85",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, our DA and qualitative analysis found GPT-4o's judgments inconsistent for African languages, and sentence-by-sentence translation proved more effective for some languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q86",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We evaluated only a small subset of the numerous multilingual LLMs available."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q87",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Our experiments were also limited by the context length of the LLMs, particularly for open LLMs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q88",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Except for LLama3.1, all other open LLMs have a context length of 8192 tokens, while encoder-decoder models were primarily based on T5."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q89",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "This makes it difficult to use the context length beyond a certain limit, making full document translation infeasible."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q90",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "LLMs are prone to variance in performance based on the prompt."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q91",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We therefore evaluated them for translation using three different prompts."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q92",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "However, it is possible that our prompts were not optimal."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q93",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Africa is home to thousands of indigenous languages, many of which exhibit unique linguistic properties. However, due to the high cost of translation using human translators and limited available funding, it is currently impossible to cover all languages. As a result, we focused on just five languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q94",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "AFRIDOC-MT is a multi-way parallel dataset. However, due to the cost of running inference over three prompts and across all 30 translation directions for all the models evaluated, most of our analysis is limited to translation tasks between English and the five African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q95",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "While we fine-tuned NLLB-200, LLama3.1 and LLaMAX3 on all 30 directions, we only provide results from NLLB-200 for all directions both before and after fine-tuning for sentence-level and pseudo-document tasks in the Appendix D."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q96",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Quality evaluation in MT is an open and ongoing area of research, especially for document-level translation. Recent works have proposed embedding-based metrics for evaluation at both the sentence and document levels. While this has been well explored for high-resource language pairs, it remains underexplored for African languages, although there is a tool, AfriCOMET, that works for sentence-level evaluation in African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q97",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, we evaluated the document-level translation outputs using ModernBERT-base-long-context-qe-v1, trained on the WMT human evaluation dataset across 41 language pairs, including over 20 languages and three African languages (Hausa, Xhosa, and Zulu), two of which are included to our work."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q98",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, the scores were nearly identical across all models, offering no meaningful differentiation. Hence, for our document-level evaluation, in addition to lexical-based metrics, we incorporated three other evaluation approaches: using GPT-4o as a judge, human evaluation, and qualitative analysis."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q99",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "GPT-4o was employed to assess and rate the translation outputs of four models. While its ratings were consistent for translations into English, the same was not observed for translations into African languages, likely due to the model's limited understanding of these languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q100",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Therefore, we conducted a human evaluation for translations from English to African languages, comparing only three models due to cost constraints. However, we were unable to recruit annotators for Zulu."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q101",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "While we fine-tuned both NLLB-1.3B and LLaMAX3 models across all 30 language directions, due to computational constraints and the high cost of qualitative evaluation, our detailed analysis focuses only on translation between English and the 5 African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q102",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Nevertheless, we report quantitative results across all 30 directions for NLLB-1.3B. We will make all fine-tuned models publicly available to support future work, and we hope that further research will explore the remaining translation directions in greater depth."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q103",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "A potential limitation of our dataset is the influence of translationese (Koppel and Ordan, 2011). Since all source material translated originates in English, translated sentences in African languages may exhibit patterns such as unnatural syntax or overly literal phrasing."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q104",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Although we have not conducted an analysis to quantify these effects, prior work suggests that they can affect MT model performance, generalization and evaluation including direct assessment (Freitag et al., 2019; Edunov et al., 2020)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q105",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Furthermore, AFRIDOC-MT may reflect a bias toward English in terms of structure, semantics, and cultural framing. We leave a deeper investigation of these issues to future work."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q106",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "AFRIDOC-MT was created with the utmost consideration for ethical standards. The English texts translated were sourced from publicly available and ethically sourced materials. The data sources were selected to represent different cultural perspectives, with a focus on minimizing any potential bias."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q107",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Efforts were made to ensure the dataset does not include harmful, biased, or offensive content via manual inspection."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q108",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "This work was carried out with support from Lacuna Fund, an initiative co-founded by The Rockefeller Foundation, Google.org, and Canada's International Development Research Centre. This research project has benefited from the Microsoft Accelerate Foundation Models Research (AFMR)"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q109",
      "page": 11,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Also, we also appreciate the translators whose names we have listed below: 1. Amharic: Bereket Tilahun, Hana M. Tamiru, Biniam Asmlash, Lidetewold Kebede 2. Hausa: Junaid Garba, Umma Abubakar, Jibrin Adamu, Ruqayya Nasir Iro 3. Swahili: Mohamed Mwinyimkuu, Laanyu koone, Baraka Karuli Mgasa, Said Athumani Said 4. Yorùbá: Ifeoluwa Akinsola, Simeon Onaolapo, Ganiyat Dasola Afolabi, Oluwatosin Koya 5. Zulu: Busisiwe Pakade, Rooweither Mabuya, Tholakele Zungu, Zanele Thembani"
    },
    {
