    {
      "id": "Q118",
      "page": 18,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Each file contains 2500 sentences, and they are named in the format of a serial number followed by your first name."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q119",
      "page": 18,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Please do not delete double empty rows, as they serve to separate paragraphs. Also, avoid deleting any rows, columns, or provided text."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q120",
      "page": 18,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Use the language field to input the translations. It is essential not to rely on translation engines, as our quality assurance process can detect this. Depending on such tools may result in potential issues that you would need to address, leading to additional work on your part."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q121",
      "page": 18,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We will provide a list of extracted terminologies soon so that you can harmonize how terminologies are translated."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q122",
      "page": 18,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The files are in .csv format, and you can open them using Google Sheets or Microsoft Excel (for offline work)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q123",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Given that the translated documents vary in length in terms of sentences and tokens, and considering the maximum token length limitations of the different LLMs used, we adopted a chunking approach for document-level evaluation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q124",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "In this approach, documents were divided into smaller pseudo-documents that fit within the maximum length constraints of the models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q125",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To establish an appropriate chunk size, each document was divided into fixed-size chunks of k sentences, with the possibility that the final chunk may contain fewer than k sentences."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q126",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We conducted an initial analysis, testing different values for k (5, 10, and 25), with k=1 serving as our sentence-level setup."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q127",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Our analysis revealed that Amharic and Yorùbá—languages with unique characteristics such as non-Latin scripts and diacritics, respectively—had the largest average token counts across the tokenizers."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q128",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To accommodate both languages in our experiments, we chose pseudo-documents with k=10."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q129",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "However, for the SFT models described in Appendix B.2, we used both k=5 and k=10."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q130",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "M2M-100 (Fan et al., 2020) is a transformer-based multilingual neural translation model from Meta, trained to translate between 100 languages, including several African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q131",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "It has three variants of different sizes: 400M parameters, 1.2B parameters, and 12B parameters."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q132",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For our experiments, we evaluated the 400M and 1.2B variants."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q133",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "NLLB (NLLB Team et al., 2024) is a model similar to M2M-100, with broader coverage, trained to translate between just over 200 languages, including more than 50 African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q134",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "It also has different sizes: 600M, 1.3B, 3.3B, and 54B parameters."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q135",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For this work, we evaluated the first three variants."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q136",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "MADLAD-400 (Kudugunta et al., 2023) is a multilingual translation model based on the T5 architecture (Raffel et al., 2020), covering 450 languages, including many African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q137",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "It was trained on data collected from the Common Crawl dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q138",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The dataset underwent a thorough self-audit to filter out noisy content and ensure its quality for training MT models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q139",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Toucan (Elmadany et al., 2024; Adebara et al., 2024) is another multilingual but Afro-centric translation model based on the T5 architecture, covering 150 language pairs of African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q140",
      "page": 19,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "It was first pre-trained on large multilingual texts covering over 500 African languages and then finetuned on translation task covering over 100 language pairs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q141",
      "page": 20,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Aya-101 (Üstün et al., 2024) is an instruction-tuned mT5 model (Xue et al., 2021) designed to handle both discriminative and generative multilingual tasks. With 13B parameters, it covers 100 languages and is capable of translating between a wide range of languages, including African languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q142",
      "page": 20,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Gemma2 (Gemma Team et al., 2024) is a decoder-only LLM trained on billions of tokens sourced from the web. The training data primarily consists of English-language text, but it also includes code and mathematical content. While Gemma2 has an English-centric focus, it also possesses multilingual capabilities. We evaluate the base Gemma2 model with 9B parameters, as well as its instruction-tuned version."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q143",
      "page": 20,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "LLama3.1 (Dubey et al., 2024) is another decoder-only LLM trained on trillions of tokens across multiple languages. It was fine-tuned using existing instruction datasets as well as synthetically generated instruction data to create its instruction-tuned version. One advantage LLama3.1 has over other models is its context window of 128K tokens, the largest among all models considered in this work, making it particularly suitable for document-based tasks such as document-level translation. We evaluate the base LLama3.1 model with 8B parameters, as well as its instruction-tuned version."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q144",
      "page": 20,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "LLaMAX3 (Lu et al., 2024) is a multilingual LLM built on the LLama3 with 8B parameters as its base. It was trained on 102 languages, including several African languages, through continued pretraining. Using an English instruction dataset (Alpaca), it was further fine-tuned to create LLaMAX3-Alpaca. We evaluated both models and compared their performance across various tasks."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q145",
      "page": 20,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We perform supervised fine-tuning to tailor LLMs for translation tasks. To train sentence-level MT systems, we use all parallel sentences from AFRIDOC-MT to construct the training set, enabling the LLMs to translate across multiple directions and domains. Following Zhu et al. (2024b), we augment the parallel data with translation instructions, which are randomly sampled from a predefined set of 31 MT instructions for each training example."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q146",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To train document-level MT systems, we follow the same process, but train on longer segments formed by concatenating multiple sentences."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q147",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "When fine-tuning, we use a learning rate of 5e−6 and an effective batch size of 64."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q148",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Models are trained for only one epoch, as further training does not result in improvements and may even lead to performance degradation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q149",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "we fine-tuned the 1.3B version of NLLB-200 for sentence and pseudo-document (with 10 sentences) translation using the Fairseq (Ott et al., 2019) codebase."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q150",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We used all the training examples from 30 language directions across both domains."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q151",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The model was fine-tuned for 50k steps using a learning rate of 5e−5, token batch size of 2048 and a gradient accumulation of 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q152",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The checkpoint with the lowest validation loss was selected as the best model for evaluation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q153",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "The models were evaluated using different tools. For example, both the NLLB-200 and M2M-100 models were evaluated with the Fairseq codebase, while Toucan and MADLAD-400 were evaluated using the Hugging Face (HF) codebase."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q154",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "All other LLMs, including LLama3.1 (both instruction-tuned and SFT models), Gemma, and Aya-101, were evaluated using EleutherAI LM Evaluation Harness (lm-eval) tool (Biderman et al., 2024)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q155",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In all cases, greedy decoding was used."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q156",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The models evaluated have different context lengths. For encoder-decoder models, M2M-100 and NLLB have a maximum sequence length of 1024 and 512 respectively."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q157",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Aya-101 and MADALAD, based on the T5 architecture, do not have a pre-specified maximum sequence length, so we fixed their maximum sequence length to 1024 for all experiments involving encoder-decoder models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q158",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "However, for decoder-only models, Gemma and LLaMAX3 (based on LLama3) have a maximum sequence length of 8192, while LLama3.1 has a maximum sequence length of 128K."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q159",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Since all the decoder-only models were evaluated using LM Evaluation Harness, we used a similar setup for them, selecting the maximum length based on the specific needs of each model."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q160",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "These numbers were chosen based on the statistics from Table 11."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q161",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "However, for Amharic, when translating pseudo-documents with 25 sentences and full documents, there were instances exceeding the 95th percentile derived from the training statistics."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q162",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Therefore, we increased the token limit specifically for Amharic."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q163",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "While the translation models we evaluated do not require prompts, MADLAD-400, requires a prefix of the form <2xx> token, which is prepended to the source sentence."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q164",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Similarly, Toucan uses just the target language ISO-693 code as prefix, which is prepended to the source sentence (e.g., \"swa\" for Swahili)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q165",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For other models, including Aya-101, we used three different prompts for sentence-level translation and document translation experiments."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q166",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "The main difference between the prompts for these tasks is the explicit mention of \"text\" or \"document\" within the prompt, as shown in Table 23."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q167",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For the base models Gemma2, Llama3.1, LLaMAX3, and Aya-101, we prompted them directly using the respective prompts."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q168",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, for the instruction-tuned versions of Gemma2 and Llama3.1, we used their respective chat templates."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q169",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For all Alpaca-based models, including our SFT models, we used the Alpaca template."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q170",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We evaluate translation quality with BLEU (Papineni et al., 2002) and ChrF (Popović, 2015) using SacreBLEU (Post, 2018)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q171",
      "page": 21,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We run significance tests using bootstrap resampling and report the 95%"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q172",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We also use AfriCOMET (Wang et al., 2024a) to evaluate the quality of the translation outputs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q173",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We report the chrF scores of the best prompt for each model and language direction in the main paper, with all additional results provided in the Appendix C."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q174",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For document-level experiments, we evaluated the LLMs using the same three prompts as in the sentence-level experiment."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q175",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For evaluation, we used BLEU and chrF scores but excluded AfriCOMET due to its backbone model, AfroXLM-R-L (Alabi et al., 2022; Adelani et al., 2024a), having a context length of 512 tokens."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q176",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "This made it impractical to compute COMET scores for document-level outputs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q177",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We use GPT-4o to assess the quality of translation output, as demonstrated by Sun et al. (2025), which shows a correlation with human judgment."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q178",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Due to the cost of this task, we limited our evaluation to a few selected models, including Aya-101, GPT-3.5, GPT-4o, and LLaMAX3 fine-tuned on AFRIDOC-MT sentences and pseudo-documents of 10 sentences."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q179",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "We compared translations performed at the sentence-level and pseudo-document level in terms of fluency, content errors, and cohesion errors—specifically lexical (LE) and grammatical (GE) errors—using the same definitions as Sun et al. (2025)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q180",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "GPT-4o is prompted to rate the fluency of a document on a scale from 1 to 5, where 5 indicates high fluency and 1 represents low fluency."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q181",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "This evaluation is conducted without providing any reference document."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q182",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For the final fluency score, we report the average rating across all documents."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q183",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "GPT-4 is prompted to identify and list the mistakes, such as incorrect translations, omissions, additions, and any other errors, by comparing the model's output to the reference translation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q184",
      "page": 22,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "After identifying these errors, we count all of them and compute the average across all documents, reporting that as the content error (CE)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q185",
      "page": 23,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Cohesion: GPT-4 is prompted to rate cohesion-related mistakes, including lexical and grammatical errors, in the model's output, comparing it to the reference translation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q186",
      "page": 23,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "We count each error individually, compute the average across the documents, and report them as lexical errors (LE) and grammatical errors (GE)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q187",
      "page": 23,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Cohesion refers to how different parts of a text are connected using language structures like grammar and vocabulary."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q188",
      "page": 23,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "It ensures that sentences flow smoothly and the text makes sense as a whole."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q189",
      "page": 23,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Lexical Cohesion Mistakes: Issues with vocabulary usage, incorrect or missing synonyms, or overuse of certain words that disrupt the flow."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q190",
      "page": 23,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Grammatical Cohesion Mistakes: Problems with pronouns, conjunctions, or grammatical structures that link sentences and clauses."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q191",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Fluency can only have values between 1 and 5. However, the other metrics, including CE, GE, and LE, do not have a specific range and can take on any value because they are counts."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q192",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Beyond using GPT-4o as a judge, we also conduct human evaluation on a subset of outputs from GPT-3.5, LLaMAX3-SFT1, and LLaMAX3-SFT10 for two domains, focusing specifically on translation into five African languages due to cost constraints."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q193",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Translation into English was excluded, as existing automatic metrics, including GPT-based evaluations, are already reliable for this direction."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q194",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "For the human evaluation, three native speakers of the African languages—primarily translators involved in the dataset creation—were recruited."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q195",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Each annotator was assigned 80 documents to evaluate, tasked with marking as many error spans as possible and rating the overall quality on a scale from 0 to 100."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q196",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "This annotation followed the error span annotation (ESA) (Kocmi et al., 2024) protocol as implemented within the Appraise Evaluation Framework (Federmann, 2018)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q197",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "To assess consistency and inter-annotator agreement, 30 of the 80 documents were shared among all three annotators."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q198",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Each annotator was remunerated with $55.15"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q199",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Alongside the human direct assessment of the translation outputs, we shared a subset of the outputs with one author per language, each a native speaker."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q200",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "They were tasked with analyzing the outputs to answer two key questions: (1) What common errors or flaws do the models exhibit across different setups? and (2) How fluent are the translation outputs produced by the models across the various settings?"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q201",
      "page": 24,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Given that AFRIDOC-MT is a document-level translation dataset, and due to the limited context length of most translation models and LLMs, which makes it impossible to translate a full document at once, we opted to translate the sentences within the documents and then merge them back to form the complete document. For document-level evaluation, we split the documents into chunks of 10 sentences and translate these chunks using the different models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q202",
      "page": 25,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In Tables 19 and 20 we provide the full results on the merged pseudo-documents using d-chrF and d-BLEU."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q203",
      "page": 25,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "It is important to note that we also trained and evaluated NLLB-200 for pseudo-document translation. However, due to its 512-token maximum sequence length, it is not competitive."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q204",
      "page": 25,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Our results show that both LLama3.1 and LLaMAX3 models, when fine-tuned on sentences, performed significantly worse on pseudo-document evaluations compared to the same models fine-tuned on pseudo-documents for both domains."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q205",
      "page": 25,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "All these models were trained using a similar setup, with the primary difference being the data used for fine-tuning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q206",
      "page": 25,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Overall, no clear trend is observed in MT performance across language family classes. However, Amharic (a non-Latin script language) and Yorùbá (a heavily diacriticitized language) result in the lowest chrF scores, while Swahili—the most widely spoken indigenous African language—performs best."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q207",
      "page": 25,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In Tables 21 and 22 we present the average GPT-4o evaluation results for four models."
